<font color="#FF0000">ANOTHER LIGHT ON THE SUBJECT</font><br>
<tt>Tue May  6  0:45:01 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The new book &quot;Dereliction of Duty&quot; by Maj.H.R.McMasters proffers the thesis that the decisions of Johnson, MacNamara, and there advisors coupled with the abdication of their advisory responsibilities by the Joint Chiefs virtually insured that the war would be lost even before the first combat troops were sent.  The documentary evidence backing up the author's thesis is very thorough.  He even has a White House phone log, where Johnson was talking to Sen. Richard Russell of Georgia in late summer of '64 about how Vietnam would be a worse ordeal for the country than Korea, but that he just couldn't pull out; because the Republicans would crucify him over Vietnam the way they did to the Truman administration over China.
